## Design Thinking vs. Human-centered Design

Design thinking and human-centered design are closely related approaches to problem-solving and innovation that both place a strong emphasis on understanding the needs and perspectives of users. However, they have some key differences.

Design thinking is a broad, iterative process that involves understanding the needs of users, generating ideas, prototyping and testing solutions, and iterating until a successful solution is reached. It can be applied to a wide range of problems and contexts, and there are many different design thinking frameworks that organizations and individuals use to guide their design process.

Human-centered design, on the other hand, is a specific design approach that focuses on understanding and addressing the needs, desires, and limitations of users. It involves a deep understanding of user behavior and psychology, and often involves user research and testing to validate design decisions. Human-centered design is often used to create products, services, and experiences that are intuitive and easy to use for the people who will be using them.

While design thinking and human-centered design have some differences, they also have a lot of overlap and can be used in conjunction with each other. Many organizations and designers use a combination of both approaches to guide their design process.

